<paragraph id="1E17380F0FB677D4C27F07C35744BE83" pageId="1" pageNumber="114">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7693FBAFD30F73370C60F6874E34CE7A" pageId="1" pageNumber="114">
<taxonomicName id="BF3CC6A0A5B3F9C94BEB9EC5A9E49EBF" authorityName="R. J. Wang" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Spiradiclis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spiradiclis longanensis" order="Gentianales" pageId="1" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="longanensis">
<emphasis id="362C4680E37CE1E0250DD8924A912BEE" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="114">Spiradiclis longanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="15008BA41DBEC933E5A61DD4F4F8FC9E" authorityName="R. J. Wang" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Spiradiclis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spiradiclis danxiashanensis" order="Gentianales" pageId="1" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="danxiashanensis">
<emphasis id="9398CEC4628CF24C877B5A85B91F5199" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="114">Spiradiclis danxiashanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which it differs by its dense hairs in stems, leaves and inflorescences, (5-)7-10 secondary veins each side, a terminal or upper axillary cymose with 5-20 small flowers, linear calyx lobes, and tubular corolla.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
